  "raw_html": "<button type='button' role='link' class='btn btn-link p-0 text-start' id='link_3' aria-label=\" H. Anjanappa & Ors.  versus A. Prabhakar & Ors. pdf\"  class='noToken' href='#' onclick=javascript:open_pdf('3','2025','2025_1_1755_1781','2025INSC121'); ><font size='4'> <strong>H. ANJANAPPA & ORS. <span class='fst-italic'> versus </span>A. PRABHAKAR & ORS. </strong>- <span class='escrText'>[2025] 1 S.C.R. 1755</span><span class='ncDisplay'>2025 INSC 121</span><input type='hidden' id='cnr' value=ESCR010005002025></button></font><br><strong>Coram : J.B. PARDIWALA<sup style=\"color: #268e97;font-size: 22px;top: 0;\" class=\"tooltip-sup\" data-tooltip=\"Author\">*</sup>, R MAHADEVAN</strong><br> Issue for Consideration Whether a transferee pendente lite has a right to be impleaded in the suit by seeking leave to appeal and in case he is not impleaded, whether he is bound by the decree passed in the said suit. Headnotes&dagger; Code of Civil Procedure, 1908 (&ldquo;CPC&rdquo;) - Order I, Rule 10, Section 146; Transfer of Property Act, 1882 (&ldquo;TP Act&rdquo;) &ndash; Section 52 discussed. Principles governing grant of leave to appeal in an impleadment application made by a third party/transferee pendente lite summarised: Held: A transferee pendente lite does not have a<br><strong class='caseDetailsTD' ><span style='color:#212F3D' > Decision Date :</span><font color='green'> 29-01-2025</font><span style='color:#212F3D' > | Case No :</span><font color='green'> CIVIL APPEAL No. 1180/2025</font><span style='color:#212F3D' > | Disposal Nature :</span><font color='green'> Appeal(s) allowed</font>   <span style='color:#212F3D' > |  Bench :</span><font color='green'> 2 Judges</font></strong><div class='row my-1 mt-2 border bg-light'><div class='col-auto'><a href='#' class='btn btn-outline-secondary btn-sm my-1' onclick=open_splitview('3','2025','2025_1_1755_1781','2025INSC121','S')><i <i class='fas fa-columns me-2'></i>Split view</a></div><div class='col-auto'><a h